"Lensing J.R., Wise D.H.","Predicted climate change alters the indirect effect of predators on an ecosystem process",2006,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","103","42",,"15502","15505",,,10.1073/pnas.0607064103,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33750378374&partnerID=40&md5=27b46c39d2689c290597fd35be445d0a","Department of Entomology, University of Kentucky, S-225 Agricultural Sciences Building North, Lexington, KY 40546-0091, United States","Lensing, J.R., Department of Entomology, University of Kentucky, S-225 Agricultural Sciences Building North, Lexington, KY 40546-0091, United States; Wise, D.H., Department of Entomology, University of Kentucky, S-225 Agricultural Sciences Building North, Lexington, KY 40546-0091, United States","Changes in rainfall predicted to occur with global climate change will likely alter rates of leaf-litter decomposition through direct effects on primary decomposers. In a field experiment replicated at two sites, we show that altered rainfall may also change how cascading trophic interactions initiated by arthropod predators in the leaf litter indirectly influence litter decomposition. On the drier site there was no interaction between rainfall and the indirect effect of predators on decomposition. In contrast, on the moister site spiders accelerated the disappearance rate of deciduous leaf litter under low rainfall, but had no, or possibly a negative, indirect effect under high rainfall. Thus, changes resulting from the more intense hydrological cycle expected to occur with climate change will likely influence how predators indirectly affect an essential ecosystem process. © 2006 by The National Academy of Sciences of the USA.","Detrital food web; Litter decomposition; Rainfall; Spiders; Trophic cascade","rain; arthropod; article; climate change; ecosystem; food web; hydrology; leaf litter; litter decomposition; nonhuman; predator; prediction; priority journal; spider; trophic cascade; Animals; Climate; Ecosystem; Food Chain; Insects; Predatory Behavior; Rain; Soil; Spiders; Araneae; Arthropoda",,"Soil",,,,"Houghton, J.T., (1997) Global Warming: The Complete Briefing, , Cambridge Univ Press, Cambridge, UK; (2001) Climate Change 2001: Impacts, Adaptation, and Vulnerability, , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (Cambridge Univ Press, Cambridge, UK); Griffen, D.M., (1963) Biol Rev, 38, pp. 141-166; Schnürer, J., Clarholm, M., Boström, S., Rosswall, T., (1986) Microb Ecol, 12, pp. 217-230; Harrington, R., Woiwod, I., Sparks, T., (1999) Trends Ecol Evol, 14, pp. 146-150; Stenseth, N.C., Mysterud, A., Ottersen, G., Hurrell, J.W., Chan, K., Lima, M., (2002) Science, 297, pp. 1292-1296; Walther, G., Post, E., Convey, P., Menzel, A., Parmesan, C., Beebee, T.J.C., Fromentin, J., Bairlein, F., (2002) Nature, 416, pp. 389-395; Schmitz, O.J., Post, E., Burns, C.E., Johnston, K.M., (2003) Bioscience, 53, pp. 1199-1205; Pace, M.L., Cole, J.J., Carpenter, S.R., Kitchell, J.F., (1999) Trends Ecol Evol, 14, pp. 483-488; Scheu, S., Setälä, H., (2002) Mukitrophic Level Interactions, pp. 223-266. , eds Tscharntke T, Hawkins BA (Cambridge Univ Press, Cambridge, UK); Wardle, D.A., (2002) Communities and Ecosystems: Linking the Aboveground and Belowground Components, , Princeton Univ Press, Princeton; Lawrence, K.L., Wise, D.H., (2004) Pedobiologia, 48, pp. 149-157; Kajak, A., Chmielewski, K., Kaczmarek, M., Rembialkowska, E., (1991) Pol Ecol Stud, 17, pp. 289-310; Kajak, A., (1997) Agric Ecosyst Environ, 64, pp. 53-63; Kajak, A., (1995) Eur J Entomol, 92, pp. 573-580; Lawrence, K.L., Wise, D.H., (2000) Pedobiologia, 44, pp. 33-39; Lussenhop, J., (1992) Adv Ecol Res, 23, pp. 1-33; Toft, S., Wise, D.H., (1999) Oecologia, 119, pp. 191-197; Wise, D.H., (2004) Pedobiologia, 48, pp. 181-188; Bengtsson, G., Hedlund, K., Rundgren, S., (1993) Oecologia, 93, pp. 296-302; Hasegawa, M., Takeda, H., (1995) Pedobiologia, 39, pp. 155-169; (1998) Climate Change and